---
import Callout from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/Callout.astro";
import ContentSection from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/ContentSection.astro";
import InlineCode from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/InlineCode.astro";
import DocsPage from "../../layouts/DocsPage.astro";
import { href } from "../../lib/link";

export const prerender = true;
---

<DocsPage
	title="swipe-bar vs shadcn sheet"
	description="When to pick shadcn sheet over swipe-bar. Short honest guide on the modal dialog vs gesture drawer trade-off in React."
>
	<ContentSection label="Different shapes of the same thing">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			shadcn <InlineCode>&lt;Sheet&gt;</InlineCode> and swipe-bar look
			similar on the screen, a panel slides in from a side, but they
			solve different problems.
		</p>
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			shadcn Sheet is a <strong class="text-white/85">modal dialog</strong>
			wrapped in a slide-in animation. It's Radix Dialog under the
			hood. You open it, you do the thing, you close it. Open or closed
			is the entire state space. Accessibility, focus trap, and
			dismissal come from the Radix contract.
		</p>
		<p class="text-white/60 leading-relaxed">
			swipe-bar is a <strong class="text-white/85">gesture drawer</strong>.
			Users drag to peek, release to commit, flick to dismiss. The
			panel is part of the layout grammar of the app, not a modal
			interruption. Multi instance on the same edge and mid anchor
			bottom sheets are the shape.
		</p>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="When to pick shadcn sheet">
		<Callout type="tip" title="Pick shadcn Sheet when">
			You want a modal that opens from a side. Settings panels,
			filter dialogs, command palettes, confirmation flows. The user
			clicks a button, the panel appears, they finish, it closes. You
			don't need drag gestures, snap points, or multi instance. You're
			already on Radix or shadcn, and reusing those primitives is a
			win. Desktop first UI where touch gestures aren't central.
		</Callout>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="When to pick swipe-bar">
		<Callout type="info" title="Pick swipe-bar when">
			The panel is a persistent part of the layout: navigation,
			settings, filters that the user opens and closes many times in a
			session, often by dragging. You need mobile-native drawer feel
			with spring physics, edge swipe detection, and mouse parity on
			desktop. You want multi instance on the same side, or a bottom
			sheet with a mid anchor stop.
		</Callout>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Looking for a gesture peer?">
		<p class="text-white/60 leading-relaxed">
			If you've already decided you want a gesture driven drawer and
			you're comparing swipe-bar to something in the same category,
			the more relevant peer is Vaul, not shadcn Sheet. Head to the
			<a href={href("/docs/vs-vaul")} class="text-accent hover:underline">
				swipe-bar vs Vaul
			</a>
			comparison for a detailed matrix.
		</p>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Next steps">
		<ul class="space-y-2 text-white/60">
			<li>
				<a href={href("/docs/vs-vaul")} class="text-accent hover:underline">vs Vaul</a> — the same-category gesture drawer comparison
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href={href("/docs/getting-started")} class="text-accent hover:underline">Getting started</a> — install and wire up a sidebar
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href={href("/docs/bottom-sheets")} class="text-accent hover:underline">Bottom sheets</a> — mid anchor and full sheet patterns
			</li>
		</ul>
	</ContentSection>
</DocsPage>
